.TH CMT_FAR 3 "LIBCMT" "CMT_FAR" "FAR Memory Attribute"

.SH NAME
CMT_FAR \- FAR pointer/memory qualifier for 16-bit segmented systems

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #define INCL__FAR
.br
.B #include <LIBCMT/LIBCMT.h>

.SH FILES
LIBCMT/ATTRIBUTES/FAR.h

.SH DESCRIPTION
CMT_FAR provides the FAR qualifier used on 16-bit architectures to access memory beyond the current 64KB segment.
On modern 32/64-bit systems it normally expands to an empty token.

.SH MACROS
.TP
.B FAR
Marks a variable, pointer, struct, or function pointer as far.
On 16-bit systems this expands to "far" or compiler-specific equivalents.

.SH USAGE
On real-mode/16-bit compilers it enables addressability of memory outside the current segment.
On modern systems it is ignored but remains syntactically valid for portability.

.SH EXAMPLES
Far variable:
.nf
FAR int far_var;
.fi

Far pointer:
.nf
FAR char *far_ptr;
.fi

Far struct:
.nf
struct FAR S {
    int id;
    char name[20];
};
.fi

Far function pointer:
.nf
FAR void (*far_function)(void);
.fi

Near vs far:
.nf
int near_ptr;
int FAR far_ptr;
.fi

.SH NOTES
- Near pointers use 16-bit offsets.
- Far pointers use segment:offset addressing (32-bit).
- Far pointers are slower due to segment switching.
- Only required when targeting real-mode, MS-DOS, Turbo C, Watcom, or any memory-segmented 16-bit environment.
- This file avoids conditional compilation to maximize compatibility with older toolchains.

